  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Valid Parentheses\n\nReturn whether every opening bracket in `s` is closed by the same type of bracket in the correct order.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"()[]{}\"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"([{}])\"\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: s = \"(]\"\nOutput: false\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Input sizes follow the original interview-style constraints.\n- Return values must match the described behavior.",
  "editorial": "Use a stack to keep unresolved items. When a new token, bar, or value resolves earlier items, pop them and update the answer.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def isValid(self, s):\n        pairs = {')': '(', ']': '[', '}': '{'}\n        stack = []\n        for ch in s:\n            if ch in pairs:\n                if not stack or stack.pop() != pairs[ch]:\n                    return False\n            else:\n                stack.append(ch)\n        return not stack\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A stack is useful when the most recent unresolved item should be handled first.",
    "Keep extra state on the stack when constant-time queries are needed."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def isValid(self, s):\n        pass\n"
  },
